<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width">
<title>replit</title>
<link href="../css/recipe.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
</head>

<body>
<h1>Blueberry Muffins</h1>
<h2>Logan Bindas</h2>
<p>Muffins are the perfect way to start your morning or to just have as a snack, To better muffins it good to add fruit like blueberrys. A muffin is an individually portioned baked product, however the term can refer to one of two distinct items: a part-raised flatbread that is baked and then cooked on a griddle, or a quickbread that is chemically leavened and then baked in a mold</p>
<h3>Ingredients</h3>
<li>2 cups all-purpose flour</li>
<li>3 teaspoons baking powder</li>
<li>½ teaspoon salt</li>
<li>¾ cup white sugar</li>
<li>1 egg</li>
<li>1 cup milk</li>
<li>¼ cup vegetable oil</li>
<li>1 cup fresh blueberries.</li>
<h3>Steps</h3>
<li> Step 1: Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F (200 degrees C). Grease a 12-cup muffin tin or line cups with paper liners.</li>
<li> Step 2: Stir flour, baking powder, salt, and sugar together in a large bowl; make a well in the center.</li>
<li> Step 3: Beat egg with a fork in a small bowl or 2-cup measuring cup; whisk in milk and oil. Pour egg mixture all at once into flour mixture; mix quickly and lightly with a fork until just moistened. The batter will be lumpy. Pour blueberrys into batter. Spoon batter into the prepared muffin cups, filling each 3/4 full.</li>
<li> Step 4: Bake in the preheated oven until tops spring back when lightly pressed, about 25 minutes.</li>
<h3>Final Product</h3>
<img src="../imgs/muffin.jpg" width="600" height="300"/>
<h3>Alt recipe</h3>
<a href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/2868-jordan-marshs-blueberry-muffins"> Link for alt recipe</a>
<h3>Video of steps</h3>
<iframe width="600" height="300" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/gN-orgrgvU8" title="Easy Blueberry Muffins Recipe" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>

MY PROJECTS PAGE

Instructions - goes with Unit 3 Lesson 1 Navigations

  1. Create an index file that will hold the navigation menu that will eventually link to all of your best projects you have done this semester: Quote, MyLifeInPictures, Menu, textWrap, and Recipe.
  2. Create a horizontal navigation bar, don't worry about the links yet we will put those in as we progress through this project. Should be complete by the end of lesson 2

Instructions - goes with Unit 3 Lesson 2 Semantics

  1. Do the following AFTER Lesson 2 on Semantics. Style your main page with HTML 5 Semantics. Looking for a header, a nav, a main and a footer. Put your nav inside the header. In main just fill with lorem ipsum for now.
  2. Create an img folder
  3. Go to your quote page and download the background image, then upload it into the image folder you created in step 3.
  4. Create a css folder
  5. Go into this css folder and create a new file called quotestyle.css. Copy your entire css file from your old replit quote project into this file. Change the background image property so it looks like this ../img/nameOfYourImageHere
  6. Create a new file called quote.html and copy the entire html file from your old replit into this file. Change the link to the css file to the following ../css/quotestyle.css
  7. Go to the index page and link the quote anchor to your quote.html page. It should look like this 
<li><a href="quote.html">Quote Page</a></li>

  1. Repeat steps 4,6-8 for my life in pictures. Create a new file called lifeInPix.html, etc

  2. Repeat steps 4,6-8 for Menu. Create a new file called edinaBistro.html etc

  3. Repeat steps 4,6-8 for floatTextWrap. Create a new file called textWrap.html etc

  4. Repeat steps 4,6-8 for our Gradient Activity. Create a new file called Gradient.html etc

  5. Once everything is working and propertly linking to each other, finally put a link at the bottom of each project that links back to the original page (that is our index.html). Make sure you style it in the style.css page.

Instructions - goes with Unit 3 Lesson 3 Flex and Media Query

  1. Add in a media query that changes the navigation bar to vertical when your resize the page below 600px. Hint you will also need to make it a flex display.

    Instructions - goes with Unit 3 Lesson 4 Grid

  2. After we have done lesson 4, add a photo gallery grid to your main page, again make sure it is responsive and changes at your media query point of 600 px. For instance it could be a 2 rows and 3 cols and at the break point it will go down to 1 column 6 rows.
  3. Check the rubric and make sure everything is complete. https://docs.google.com/document/d/1d3HYvsx5Oppxe_WC4z1rLNPTGk4WJjsR/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=109423369563114655120&rtpof=true&sd=true
